            <!-- Reading Section -->
            <div class="section" id="reading">
                <h2>Reading: Hannah Arendt and The Banality of Evil</h2>
                <div class="reading-container">
                    <div class="reading-nav">
                        <button class="page-btn active" onclick="showReadingPage(1, this)">Eichmann's Trial</button>
                        <button class="page-btn" onclick="showReadingPage(2, this)">Arendt's Theory</button>
                        <button class="page-btn" onclick="showReadingPage(3, this)">Modern Implications</button>
                        <button class="page-btn" onclick="showReadingPage(4, this)">Critical Thinking</button>
                    </div>

                    <div class="reading-page active" id="reading-page-1">
                        <h3>The Eichmann Trial and a Disturbing Reality</h3>
                        <p>
                            In 1961, Adolf Eichmann stood trial in Jerusalem for crimes against humanity. As one of the key architects of the Holocaust, many expected to see a monster - a personification of pure evil. Instead, what emerged was something far more unsettling: a <span class="vocab-link" onclick="showPopup('banal', 'Lacking originality or excitement; dull and ordinary')">banal</span>, ordinary <span class="vocab-link" onclick="showPopup('bureaucratic', 'Following rules and procedures excessively, often without thinking')">bureaucratic</span> official who seemed more like a dull clerk than a sadistic mastermind.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Eichmann's defense was simple: he was merely following orders within a <span class="vocab-link" onclick="showPopup('totalitarianism', 'A system of government that demands total obedience and controls every aspect of life')">totalitarian</span> system. He claimed no personal hatred toward Jews and described his work with the <span class="vocab-link" onclick="showPopup('diligence', 'Careful and persistent effort in work or duties')">diligence</span> of a dutiful civil servant. This was not the dramatic confrontation with evil that many had anticipated, but rather a mundane administrative discussion about logistics and procedures.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Philosopher Hannah Arendt, who covered the trial for The New Yorker, was struck by this contradiction. How could such horrific crimes be committed by someone who appeared so unremarkable? Eichmann seemed to lack the dramatic malevolence that people associated with such <span class="vocab-link" onclick="showPopup('atrocious', 'Extremely cruel or shocking; horrifying')">atrocious</span> acts. He was not a psychopath or a fanatic, but rather a man who had surrendered his capacity for independent thought.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The trial revealed how easily ordinary individuals could become complicit in evil when they operated within systems that discouraged critical thinking. Eichmann's apparent normality was precisely what made his crimes so terrifying - it suggested that such evil was not the exclusive domain of monsters, but could emerge from the most mundane bureaucratic processes.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="reading-page" id="reading-page-2">
                        <h3>Arendt's Revolutionary Theory</h3>
                        <p>
                            Hannah Arendt coined the phrase "the banality of evil" to describe what she witnessed during Eichmann's trial. Her theory challenged conventional understanding of evil as something dramatic and intentional. Instead, she argued that the most dangerous evil often emerges from thoughtlessness - from people who simply stop thinking and questioning their actions.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            According to Arendt, Eichmann's evil lay not in malicious intent but in his complete abdication of moral responsibility. He had become a cog in a vast bureaucratic machine, following a <span class="vocab-link" onclick="showPopup('regimen', 'A systematic plan or set of rules to be followed')">regimen</span> of procedures without considering their moral implications. This thoughtlessness, she argued, could make ordinary people capable of extraordinary evil.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The concept suggests that evil does not require hatred, ideology, or even conscious malice. It can result from the simple failure to think, to question, to take moral responsibility for one's actions. In totalitarian systems, this thoughtlessness is systematically cultivated, creating conditions where normal people can participate in atrocities without fully comprehending the horror of their actions.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Arendt's theory was controversial because it removed the comfortable distance between "us" and "them." If evil could be banal and thoughtless rather than intentionally malicious, then anyone might be susceptible under the right circumstances. This realization <span class="vocab-link" onclick="showPopup('alienates', 'Causes someone to feel isolated or estranged from others')">alienates</span> people from their assumptions about human nature and moral certainty.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The banality of evil explains how genocide and other mass atrocities can occur without requiring a population of sadists or psychopaths. Instead, it requires only a sufficient number of people willing to stop thinking critically about their role in larger systems of harm. This makes Arendt's insight both profound and deeply unsettling for modern societies.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="reading-page" id="reading-page-3">
                        <h3>Contemporary Relevance and Applications</h3>
                        <p>
                            Arendt's concept of the banality of evil remains strikingly relevant in contemporary society. We can observe similar patterns in modern bureaucracies, corporations, and institutions where individuals participate in harmful systems while maintaining their sense of personal innocence through compartmentalization and thoughtlessness.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Consider corporate executives who implement policies leading to environmental destruction or financial ruin for ordinary people. Many of these individuals do not see themselves as evil but rather as professionals following standard business practices. Their <span class="vocab-link" onclick="showPopup('inhibitions', 'Factors that restrain or prevent someone from acting')">inhibitions</span> about causing harm are gradually eroded through bureaucratic processes that distance them from the consequences of their decisions.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Social media platforms provide another example, where content moderators and algorithm designers make decisions that can spread misinformation, promote hatred, or undermine democratic processes. Often, these individuals are not motivated by malicious intent but are simply following company protocols or technical specifications without considering the broader social implications of their work.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The banality of evil also manifests in how societies respond to systemic injustices such as poverty, racism, or climate change. Many people recognize these as serious problems but feel comfortable maintaining their current lifestyle because their individual contribution seems negligible within the larger system. This diffusion of responsibility allows collective harm to continue through individual inaction rather than active malice.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Understanding this concept is crucial for recognizing how ordinary people can become complicit in harmful systems. It emphasizes the importance of maintaining critical thinking, moral reflection, and personal responsibility even within large, complex organizations. The lesson is not that all bureaucrats or professionals are evil, but that systems can be structured in ways that make thoughtlessness and moral abdication dangerously easy.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="reading-page" id="reading-page-4">
                        <h3>The Importance of Critical Thinking</h3>
                        <p>
                            Arendt believed that the primary defense against the banality of evil was the cultivation of critical thinking and moral reflection. She argued that thinking - in the sense of questioning, examining, and judging our actions - is fundamentally a moral activity that prevents us from becoming thoughtless participants in harmful systems.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            This type of thinking requires courage because it often means questioning authority, challenging conventional wisdom, and accepting personal responsibility for difficult moral decisions. In bureaucratic or totalitarian contexts, such thinking can be professionally or personally dangerous, which is why systems of power often work to discourage it through various forms of social and institutional pressure.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Education plays a crucial role in developing this capacity for critical thinking. However, Arendt distinguished between education that simply transmits information or technical skills and education that develops judgment and moral reasoning. The former can actually contribute to the banality of evil by creating highly competent specialists who never question the broader purposes of their expertise.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The concept also highlights the importance of diverse perspectives and open dialogue in society. When people are isolated within echo chambers or institutional silos, they are more likely to lose touch with the human consequences of their actions. Exposure to different viewpoints and direct contact with those affected by our decisions can help maintain the moral imagination necessary to prevent thoughtless participation in harmful systems.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Ultimately, Arendt's insight suggests that preventing evil requires not just good intentions but active, ongoing moral engagement with the world around us. It demands that we regularly examine our roles in larger systems, question the assumptions underlying our work and social participation, and maintain empathy for those who might be harmed by our actions or inaction. This is challenging work, but it may be the price of maintaining our humanity in complex modern societies.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Vocabulary Section -->
